50|$|The {{practice}} of the King's Bench and the Court of Common Pleas differed {{during the course of}} the 16th century. In the King's Bench, it was not necessary for the plaintiff to prove the subsequent promise. The Common Pleas disagreed. Matters came to a head in Slade's Case in 1602. The case effectively established that assumpsit could be used in lieu of debt: the law would <b>imply</b> a <b>promise</b> to pay the debt from the existence of the debt itself.|$|R
